dataset.title: City of Seattle Historic forest growth and yield permanent sample plots in the lower Cedar River Municipal Watershed, Seattle, WA, USA, 1946 - 2015

creator.organizationName: City of Seattle, Seattle Public Utilities
City of Seattle, Seattle Public Utilities

abstract.para: From 1946 to 1979 watershed staff established twenty one permanent sample plots in the lower portion of the Cedar River Municipal Watershed to provide watershed managers with long term, site specific data on timber growth and yield. Installation of most of the historic permanent sample plots (PSP) occurred in the middle 1950's. Exceptions include the first two plots, for which initial measurements were completed in 1946, and two final plots, which were added to the network in 1978 and 1979, respectively.

The plots described in this document are not part of the systematic, permanent sample plot program currently being implemented in old-growth forests of the CRMW. This report provides a summary of the original PSP program, which should aid managers in determining the utility of the dataset, and the appropriateness of continued periodic historic PSP measurements for meeting forest management goals.

description.para: The original PSP network is a medley of plot sizes, plot shapes, measurements, and treatments. Measurements are, except for a few exceptions, limited to timber production parameters. Stem densities, species composition (with some exceptions), tree heights and ages typify the measurements taken on the original PSPâ€™s. Measurements taken from 2003 to 2006 also include saplings counts, shrub cover, large woody debris, and canopy cover. The 2015 resampling does not include these other metrics. In general, data quality and record keeping is reasonably high. Initial measurements are almost always well documented and of high quality. Subsequent measurements are generally well documented with a few exceptions where plot size is changed, species is missing, measurements of smaller diameter trees is excluded, or other data is missing.

personnel.organizationName: City of Seattle, Seattle Public Utilities

abstract.para: Long-term forest monitoring: Based on the evaluations of standard forest inventory and secondary forest attribute data, the City designed and conducts a long-term program of sampling and monitoring to update the forest and habitat inventory periodically over the full term of the HCP. Permanent sample plots are being re-sampled in a 5-10 year rotating panel design to detect vegetation change.
